# Design: Admin Dashboard Contract Alignment

## Technical Approach
Implement additive backend endpoints to align with current admin dashboard needs while preserving existing CSV behavior, then update frontend DTOs to consume backend contracts directly. The change follows the spec domains for jobs listing, report diagnostics, CSRF behavior, and contract drift tests.

## Architecture Decisions

### Decision: Keep CSV export endpoint unchanged; add JSON diagnostics endpoint

| Option | Tradeoff | Decision |
|---|---|---|
| Reuse `GET /{id}/report` for CSV and JSON via content negotiation | High ambiguity, fragile client behavior, harder tests | ❌ |
| Keep `GET /{id}/report` as CSV and add `GET /{id}/report/diagnostics` JSON | Additive change, low compatibility risk, clear contract split | ✅ |

### Decision: Add jobs list endpoint as read-only summary DTO

| Option | Tradeoff | Decision |
|---|---|---|
| Return full job detail graph | Larger payload, tighter coupling to internals | ❌ |
| Return minimal list item (`id,type,status,createdAt,updatedAt`) with stable sort | Small payload, clear UI contract, easier drift detection | ✅ |

### Decision: Centralize frontend DTO normalization in service layer types

| Option | Tradeoff | Decision |
|---|---|---|
| Keep UI adapters (`status/message` aliases) in page components | Hidden drift, repeated mapping logic | ❌ |
| Align service DTOs to backend names (`outcome,errorCode,errorMessage,payload`) and update pages accordingly | Small refactor in tests/pages, stronger contract fidelity | ✅ |

### Decision: CSRF token lifecycle in shared admin HTTP client

| Option | Tradeoff | Decision |
|---|---|---|
| Per-call manual header handling in each admin service | Duplication and missed endpoints risk | ❌ |
| Auto-inject `X-XSRF-TOKEN` for non-GET `/api/admin/**` requests from `XSRF-TOKEN` cookie | Single control point, consistent behavior | ✅ |

## Data Flow

`AdminCatalogJobsPage` → `adminOperationsService` → `httpClient` → `/api/admin/catalog/jobs` (list)

`AdminCatalogJobsPage` → `adminOperationsService` → `httpClient` → `/api/admin/catalog/jobs/{id}/report/diagnostics` (JSON)

`CSV download action` → `adminOperationsService` → `httpClient/fetch` → `/api/admin/catalog/jobs/{id}/report` (CSV unchanged)

For admin writes:

Browser receives `Set-Cookie: XSRF-TOKEN=...` → `httpClient` reads cookie on POST/PUT/PATCH/DELETE `/api/admin/**` → sends `X-XSRF-TOKEN` header → Spring Security validates matcher in `SecurityConfig`.

